abstract: Another day of excitement in the Pennsylvania Legislature. This morning the House resumed the second reading and consideration of the bill relating to the Sunbury and Eric Railroad, and the Cleveland Painesville and Ashtabula Company. Numerous speeches were made, and the most grave charges of bribery and corruption were uttered. Mr. SMITH, of Crawford, said that the Pittsburg and Erie Railroad Company had been ruined by building their road to the Ohio State line.

abstract: Large Incendiary Fire in Gowanus--Accidents,  A little before 2 o'clock yesterday morning, the inhabitants of that usually quiet locality Gowanus, in the Eighth Ward of Brooklyn, were aroused from their slumbers by the cry of fire. At this time, flames were to be seen issuing from the large Morocco Factory, in two different parts of the building, belonging to Messrs. MIRICK  BROS., located on the west side of Third-avenue, between Twenty-first and Twenty-second-streets.

abstract: THE NEWARK FIRE DEPARTMENT.--Majority and minority reports have been made by the Committee of the Newark Common Council, appointed to report on the probable cost of a paid Fire Department for the city. abstract: Our Government has received from Mr. SOULE the very unexpected intelligence that the Spanish Government refuses compliance with his demands made in our behalf in the Black Warrior affair. abstract: Yesterday afternoon, the work of raising the Calorie Ship Ericsson was successfully accomplished. Early in the day the men were busy at the pumps striving to free the ship of water, and the Boom-Derrick was brought alongside, to render the necessary aid. The vessel was nearly raised on Tuesday, when it was found that her anchors held her fast, having been cast out forward.

abstract: Our village was yesterday the scene of a most disastrous fire. The Elbridge Manufacturing Company's large Knitting Factory caught fire, as is supposed from friction, at about 1 P. M., and is wholly destroyed. A strong breeze was blowing at the time, and at one time eleven buildings were on fire. We are blessed with an efficient body of firemen and good apparatus, otherwise a large part of the village must have burned.

abstract: The modern Platform as an arena for speaking, is a valuable invention. Every man has sympathies with it. The only wonder is that it had to be invented. abstract: On the 26th ultimo, a sharp combat took place before Kalafat. Twenty squadrons of Russians, with six guns, were making a reconnaissance of the Turkish lines, when the Turks sallied out with two regiments of regulars, and some bayouks and cannon, and after a combat of three hours' duration, obliged the Russians to retreat with a loss of 500 men. OMAR PASHA was at Shumla, concentrating his forces, apparently for defensive measures only.

abstract: A letter sent from the United States to any place in France is invariably charged with double postage when enclosed in an envelope. The fact should be remembered by those writing to their friends in that country. In order to save postage, letters should be written very close on good thin paper, and directed without an envelope. Letters without envelopes, weighing over 7 1/2 grains (1/2 of an ounce) are charged double postage in France.

abstract: The Constitution vests the war-making power in Congress; but Congress is not belligerent enough to suit the views of fillibusters and fillibustering politicians. abstract: PRAIRIE FIRE.--The St. Anthony Express, a newspaper published at St. Pauls, Minnesota. says that the citizens of that place had for several days been "enjoying" the spectacle of a prairie on fire. abstract: THE FIREMEN'S RIOT IN MYRTLE-AVENUE. Seven firemen, charged with being concerned in this riot on Saturday night, were arrested on Wednesday, and were yesterday held in the sum of $500 each, to answer any indictment that may be brought against them. abstract: SUICIDE BY HANGING.--On Tuesday afternoon a laborer named PATRICK MURPHY, who was subject to fits of temporary insanity, committed suicide near Laurel Hill Cemetery, Queens County, by hanging himself with a cord suspended from the branch of a tree. He was in the employ of TERRENCE McGIVIGGIN, of this city, and destroyed his life while his fellow workmen were absent to dinner. Deceased was a native of Ireland, 30 years of age, and single.

abstract: A GREAT FEAT AND NARROW ESCAPE.--On Saturday, two young men, college students, about eighteen years of age, went out in a skiff over the bay on a shooting excursion. During the day they went round Lighthouse Point, and when they desired to return, were prevented by a strong head wind. All attempts to round the point being fruitless, they had to resign themselves to the control of the elements.

abstract: ARRIVAL OF A BOSTON ICE-SHIP AT MADRAS.--STATE OF THE CARGO.--The American bark Piscataqua, from Boston, has arrived at Madras. She will already have attracted the notice of all whom business or pleasure has drawn to the beach, where she presents the curious appearance of a vessel on her beam ends and about to sink. She left Boston nearly five months ago in good trim, and filled with ice, for Madras.

abstract: SINGULAR ATTACHMENT.-Upon Col. KING's plantation, near this place, there is a certain old gander, so attached to one of the milch cows that he follows her wherever she goes. He has been seen plodding at her heels several miles from home, never permitting her to escape his sight. When caught and confined, he displays the greatest uneasiness, and never ceases his squalls until he finds the object of his devotion.

abstract: MYSTERIOUS.--A gentleman came on the cars from the East, and put up at the Exchange Hotel in this city, on the 13th of April last, entering his name on the register as "H. M. BATES." His at tending physician was Prof. ALLEN, who counseled with other able physicians in the city.

abstract: The growth of Newark is commented upon by the Daily. It says the increase of population, business and improvement, has been so rapid that already the census of 1850 is getting obsolete. abstract: As was anticipated, a very large number of persons gathered in front of the City Hall yesterday after noon, for the avowed purpose of listening to the discourse of one of the street-preachers. abstract: We have: conversed with several persons acquainted with the circumstances attending the late explosion of the steamer Gazelle. which took place at Canemah on Saturday morning last. It seems to be the settled opinion of everybody that this melancholy accident, which caused the most intense anguish in the hearts of hundreds of our citizens, and spread a gloom over the entire community, was attributable to the reckless carelessness or total incompetency of the engineer.

abstract: The Bellevilie (II.) Tribune publishes an account of a terrible storm which visited St. Clair County on the 16th inst. The first intimation of the approach of a storm was given by the leaves and twigs which filled the air, some of which had come from a considerable distance. The tornado, it is supposed originated in Missouri, several miles below St. Louis, and crossed over to the Illinois side.

abstract: In yesterday morning's TIMES, we published all of interest that had transpired in Boston relative to the proceedings, in and out of Court, in the case of the fugitive BURNS.
